{"title_page": "1992 United States presidential election in Massachusetts", "text_new": "{{Main|1992 United States presidential election}}\n{{Infobox Election\n| election_name = 1992 [[United States presidential election]] in Massachusetts\n| country = Massachusetts\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1988 United States presidential election in Massachusetts\n| previous_year = 1988\n| next_election = 1996 United States presidential election in Massachusetts\n| next_year = 1996\n| election_date = November 3, 1992\n| image_size = x160px\n| image1 = Bill Clinton.jpg\n| nominee1 = '''[[Bill Clinton]]'''\n| party1 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| home_state1 = [[Arkansas]]\n| running_mate1 = '''[[Al Gore]]'''\n| electoral_vote1 = '''12'''\n| popular_vote1 = '''1,318,662'''\n| percentage1 = '''47.54%'''\n| image2 = George H. W. Bush presidential portrait (cropped 2).jpg\n| nominee2 = [[George H. W. Bush]]\n| party2 = Republican Party (United States)\n| home_state2 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate2 = [[Dan Quayle]]\n| electoral_vote2 = 0\n| popular_vote2 = 805,049\n| percentage2 = 29.03%\n| image3 = RossPerotColor.jpg\n| nominee3 = [[Ross Perot]]\n| party3 = Independent (politician)\n| home_state3 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate3 = [[James Stockdale]]\n| electoral_vote3 = 0\n| popular_vote3 = 632,312\n| percentage3 = 22.80%\n| map_image = Massachusetts Election Results by County, 1992.svg\n| map_size = 401px\n| map_caption = County Results\n'''Clinton'''\n{{legend|#d3e7ff|30\u201340%}}\n{{legend|#b9d7ff|40\u201350%}}\n{{legend|#86b6f2|50\u201360%}}\n{{legend|#4389e3|60\u201370%}}\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[George H. W. Bush]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| after_party = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n\n{{ElectionsMA}}\n\nThe '''1992 United States presidential election in Massachusetts''' took place on November 3, 1992, as part of the [[1992 United States presidential election]]. Voters chose 12 representatives, or electors to the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]], who voted for [[President of the United States|president]] and [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]].\n\n[[Massachusetts]] was won by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[List of governors of Arkansas|Governor]] [[Bill Clinton]] of [[Arkansas]] with 47.54% of the popular vote over incumbent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] President [[George H. W. Bush]] of [[Texas]] with 29.03%. [[Independent politician|Independent]] businessman [[Ross Perot]] of Texas finished in third, with 22.80% of the popular vote.<ref name=results/> Clinton thus defeated Bush in the state with a margin of 18.52%.<ref>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1992|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nMassachusetts weighed in as a solid 13% more Democratic than the national average in 1992.\n\nBush failed to carry a single county in the state, and his 29.03% of the vote was the smallest vote share a Republican presidential candidate had received in Massachusetts since [[1964 United States presidential election in Massachusetts|1964]].\n\nClinton's decisive win in Massachusetts solidified the state's status in the modern era as a solid [[Red states and blue states|blue state]]. Massachusetts had been a Democratic-leaning state since [[1928 United States presidential election in Massachusetts|1928]], and a Democratic stronghold since [[1960 United States presidential election in Massachusetts|1960]]. In [[1972 United States presidential election in Massachusetts|1972]], Massachusetts was the only state in the nation to vote for Democrat [[George McGovern]] over Republican [[Richard Nixon]] in his 49-state landslide. However the state had trended Republican in the 1980s, with [[Ronald Reagan]] narrowly winning the state and [[George H. W. Bush]] taking a solid 45% and winning 3 counties in [[1988 United States presidential election in Massachusetts|1988]]. In 1992, Clinton not only carried the state by a double-digit margin, leaving Bush with less than 30% of the vote, but Clinton also swept every county in the state, as [[Secularism|secular]] [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]] [[New England]] rejected an increasingly [[Southern United States|Southern]] and [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] Republican Party dominated by [[Christian right|Evangelical Christians]]. Since then, every Democratic presidential candidate that followed has carried the state by double-digit margins and won all 14 counties in Massachusetts.\n\n==Results==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n! colspan=\"6\" | 1992 United States presidential election in Massachusetts<ref name=results>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results - Massachusetts|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1992&fips=25&f=0&off=0&elect=0&minper=0|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref>\n|-bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 15em\" |Party\n! style=\"width: 17em\" |Candidate\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Votes\n! style=\"width: 7em\" |Percentage\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Electoral votes\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | '''[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]'''\n| '''[[Bill Clinton]]'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''1,318,662'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''47.54%'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''12'''\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF3333; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| [[George H. W. Bush]] ([[incumbent]])\n| align=\"right\" | 805,049\n| align=\"right\" | 29.03%\n| al