W. Bush]]\n| party2 = Republican Party (United States)\n| home_state2 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate2 = [[Dan Quayle]]\n| electoral_vote2 = 0\n| popular_vote2 = 805,049\n| percentage2 = 29.03%\n| image3 = RossPerotColor.jpg\n| nominee3 = [[Ross Perot]]\n| party3 = Independent (politician)\n| home_state3 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate3 = [[James Stockdale]]\n| electoral_vote3 = 0\n| popular_vote3 = 632,312\n| percentage3 = 22.80%\n| map_image = Massachusetts Election Results by County, 1992.svg\n| map_size = 401px\n| map_caption = County Results\n'''Clinton'''\n{{legend|#d3e7ff|30\u201340%}}\n{{legend|#b9d7ff|40\u201350%}}\n{{legend|#86b6f2|50\u201360%}}\n{{legend|#4389e3|60\u201370%}}\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[George H. W. Bush]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| after_party = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n\n{{ElectionsMA}}\n\nThe '''1992 United States presidential election in Massachusetts''' took place on November 3, 1992, as part of the [[1992 United States presidential election]]. Voters chose 12 representatives, or electors to the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]], who voted for [[President of the United States|president]] and [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]].\n\n[[Massachusetts]] was won by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[List of governors of Arkansas|Governor]] [[Bill Clinton]] of [[Arkansas]] with 47.54% of the popular vote over incumbent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] President [[George H. W. Bush|George H.W. Bush]] of [[Texas]] with 29.03%. [[Independent politician|Independent]] businessman [[Ross Perot]] of Texas finished in third, with 22.80% of the popular vote.<ref name=results/> Clinton thus defeated Bush in the state with a margin of 18.52%.<ref>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1992|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nMassachusetts weighed in as a solid 13% more Democratic than the national average in 1992.\n\nBush failed to carry a single county in the state, and his 29.03% of the vote was the smallest vote share a Republican presidential candidate had received in Massachusetts since [[1964 United States presidential election in Massachusetts|1964]].\n\nClinton's decisive win in Massachusetts solidified the state's status in the modern era as a solid [[Red states and blue states|blue state]]. Massachusetts had been a Democratic-leaning state since [[1928 United States presidential election in Massachusetts|1928]], and a Democratic stronghold since [[1960 United States presidential election in Massachusetts|1960]]. In [[1972 United States presidential election in Massachusetts|1972]], Massachusetts was the only state in the nation to vote for Democrat [[George McGovern]] over Republican [[Richard Nixon]] in his 49-state landslide. However the state had trended Republican in the 1980s, with [[Ronald Reagan]] narrowly winning the state and [[George H. W. Bush|George H.W. Bush]] taking a solid 45% and winning 3 counties in [[1988 United States presidential election in Massachusetts|1988]]. In 1992, Clinton not only carried the state by a double-digit margin, leaving Bush with less than 30% of the vote, but Clinton also swept every county in the state, as [[Secularism|secular]] [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]] [[New England]] rejected an increasingly [[Southern United States|Southern]] and [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] Republican Party dominated by [[Christian right|Evangelical Christians]]. Since then, every Democratic presidential candidate that followed has carried the state by double-digit margins and won all 14 counties in Massachusetts.\n\n==Results==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n! colspan=\"6\" | 1992 United States presidential election in Massachusetts<ref name=results>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results - Massachusetts|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1992&fips=25&f=0&off=0&elect=0&minper=0|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref>\n|-bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 15em\" |Party\n! style=\"width: 17em\" |Candidate\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Votes\n! style=\"width: 7em\" |Percentage\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Electoral votes\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | '''[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]'''\n| '''[[Bill Clinton]]'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''1,318,662'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''47.54%'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''12'''\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF3333; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| [[George H.W. Bush]] ([[incumbent]])\n| align=\"right\" | 805,049\n| align=\"right\" | 29.03%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#DDDDDD; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n| [[Ross Perot]]\n| align=\"right\" | 632,312\n| align=\"right\" | 22.80%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFCC00; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n| [[Andre Marrou]]\n| align=\"right\" | 7,458  \n| align=\"right\" | 0.27%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF00FF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[New Alliance Party|New Alliance]]\n| [[Lenora Fulani]]\n| align=\"right\" | 3,172\n| align=\"right\" | 0.11%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#B5A642; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | Independent Voters <small>(a)</small>\n| [[Howard Phillips (politician)|Howard Phillips]]\n| align=\"right\" | 2,217\n| align=\"right\" | 0.08%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#DDDDDD; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n| Others <small>(Write-In)</small>\n| align=\"right\" | 1,870\n| align=\"right\" | 0.07%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#00BFFF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Natural Law Party|Natural Law]]\n| [[John Hagelin|Dr. John Hagelin]]\n| align=\"right\" | 1,812\n| align=\"right\" | 0.07%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#800000; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[U.S. Labor Party|Democrats for<br>Economic Recovery]]\n| [[Lyndon LaRouche]]\n| align=\"right\" | 1,007\n| align=\"right\" | 0.04%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#DC241f; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Socialist Party USA|Socialist]]\n| [[J. Quinn Brisben]] <small>(Write-In)</small>\n| align=\"right\" | 13\n| align=\"right\" | <0.01%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF00FF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Prohibition Party|Prohibition]]\n| [[Earl Dodge]] <small>(Write-In)</small>\n| align=\"right\" | 2\n| align=\"right\" | <0.01%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n|-bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| colspan=\"3\" align=\"right\" | '''Totals'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''2,773,574'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''100.0%'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''12'''\n|}\n(a) [[Howard Phillips (politician)|Howard Phillips]] was the candidate of the [[Constitution Party (United States)|U.S. Taxpayers' Party]] nationally.\n\n===Results by Congressional district===\nClinton won all 11 Congressional districts.\n{|class=wikitable\n! District\n! Bush\n! Clinton\n! Perot\n! Representative\n|- align=center\n! {{party shading/Democratic}}|{{ushr|Massachusetts|1|1st}}\n| 27%\n| '''48%'''\n| 25%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}|[[John Olver]]\n|- align=center\n! {{party shading/Democratic}}|{{ushr|Massachusetts|2|2nd}}\n| 29%\n| '''46%'''\n| 25%\n| {{party shad